"# Chapter 15: Voice & Speech

The human voice is a wind instrument with a variable resonator. Air from the lungs sets the vocal cords vibrating—a buzzy, nasal-sounding source rich in harmonics—and the throat, mouth, and nasal cavity act as a tunable filter bank, amplifying certain frequencies and suppressing others. The peaks in that filter response are called **formants**, and they give vowels their identity. \"Ah\" and \"ee\" use the same vocal-cord buzz; the tongue and jaw reshape the cavity, moving the formant peaks, and the listener hears two different vowels.

Speech belongs in the Sound book because it is synthesis: a periodic source shaped by resonators, plus bursts of noise for consonants. The Scheme we write to make a plausible \"ah\" or \"oo\" is the same additive and filter Scheme we used for bells and strings. We are not importing a voice—we are building one from sine waves, noise, and formants.

This chapter drills three ideas:

1. **Formant synthesis** — vowels as tuned resonances applied to a harmonic source.
2. **Text-to-speech (TTS)** — converting written words into audio.
3. **Speech-to-text (STT)** — converting audio back into words.

The first idea runs now. The second and third are flagged as engine gaps—teach the concept, show the Scheme, mark the seam.

---

## 1. The Vowel as a Formant Stack

A vowel is a sustained tone (the vocal-cord buzz) passed through a cascade of resonant peaks. The buzz is rich in harmonics—think of it as a sawtooth wave at the speaker's fundamental frequency, typically 85–180 Hz for adult males, 165–255 Hz for adult females.

The formants are numbered F1, F2, F3, and so on. For intelligible vowels, we need at least F1 and F2. Here are approximate formant pairs for a few English vowels, in hertz:

| Vowel | F1  | F2   |
|-------|-----|------|
| \"ee\"  | 270 | 2300 |
| \"ih\"  | 390 | 2000 |
| \"eh\"  | 530 | 1840 |
| \"ah\"  | 730 | 1090 |
| \"aw\"  | 570 | 840  |
| \"oo\"  | 300 | 870  |

We synthesize a vowel by generating a sawtooth at the speaker's pitch, then adding resonant peaks at F1 and F2. The `add-formant` verb applies a stack of resonant filters (Lorentzian peaks, each with a center frequency and bandwidth). We saw this in Chapter 7 when we gave a body to a plucked string—vowels are the same idea, just at frequencies tuned for human speech.

[VISUAL: Spectrogram showing a sawtooth at 100 Hz and two bright bands at 730 Hz (F1) and 1090 Hz (F2), labeled \"ah\"]

```scheme
;; A sustained \"ah\" vowel — sawtooth + formants at 730 and 1090 Hz
(add-formant
  (wave 'saw 120 1.0)
  '(730 1090))
```

The pitch is 120 Hz (roughly B♭ below middle C), the duration is one second, and the formants at 730 and 1090 Hz sculpt the harmonic spectrum into the shape our ears recognize as \"ah.\"

---

## 2. A Second Vowel

Change the formant frequencies, and the vowel changes. Here is \"ee\" (as in \"beet\"), with F1 at 270 Hz and F2 at 2300 Hz:

```scheme
;; Sustained \"ee\" vowel
(add-formant
  (wave 'saw 120 1.0)
  '(270 2300))
```

Same sawtooth source, different resonances. The high F2 gives \"ee\" its bright, fronted quality.

---

## 3. A Lower Female Voice

Raise the fundamental to 200 Hz (roughly G below middle C) and use the same \"ah\" formants:

```scheme
;; Female \"ah\" at 200 Hz
(add-formant
  (wave 'saw 200 1.0)
  '(730 1090))
```

The formants stay constant; the pitch rises. The vowel remains recognizable because F1 and F2 do not change.

---

## 4. A Sequence of Vowels

Concatenate three vowels—\"ah,\" \"eh,\" \"ee\"—each half a second long:

```scheme
;; A vowel sequence: ah-eh-ee
(define (vowel f1 f2 pitch dur)
  (add-formant
    (wave 'saw pitch dur)
    (list f1 f2)))

(list
  (vowel 730 1090 150 0.5)  ; ah
  (vowel 530 1840 150 0.5)  ; eh
  (vowel 270 2300 150 0.5)) ; ee
```

The formants morph; the pitch stays constant. The listener hears three distinct vowels spoken on a monotone.

---

## 5. A Chorus of One

Layer the same vowel at three different pitches to produce a chorus effect—one voice singing \"ah\" as a triad:

```scheme
;; Chorus: three voices singing \"ah\" at C-E-G (ratios 4:5:6)
(define base 130)

(list
  (add-formant (wave 'saw (* base 1.0) 2.0) '(730 1090))   ; root
  (add-formant (wave 'saw (* base 1.25) 2.0) '(730 1090))  ; major third
  (add-formant (wave 'saw (* base 1.5) 2.0) '(730 1090)))  ; fifth
```

Same formants, three pitches. The word \"chorus\" in the book spine refers to this technique—a unison vowel sung at harmonic intervals.

---

## 6. Adding a Third Formant

F3 adds realism. For \"ah,\" F3 is around 2440 Hz:

```scheme
;; \"ah\" with three formants
(add-formant
  (wave 'saw 120 1.0)
  '(730 1090 2440))
```

The difference is subtle but audible—the vowel sounds rounder, more embodied.

---

## 7. A Diphthong

A diphthong is a vowel that glides from one formant position to another. English \"I\" (as in \"bite\") starts near \"ah\" and glides toward \"ee.\" Approximate that by concatenating two vowels with no gap:

```scheme
;; Diphthong: \"ah\" → \"ee\" (approximates \"I\")
(list
  (add-formant (wave 'saw 140 0.3) '(730 1090))  ; ah
  (add-formant (wave 'saw 140 0.2) '(270 2300))) ; ee
```

The formants slide from 730/1090 to 270/2300 over half a second.

---

## 8. A Whispered Vowel

Replace the sawtooth with noise, and the vowel becomes whispered—no vocal-cord buzz, just turbulent air shaped by the formants:

```scheme
;; Whispered \"ah\"
(add-formant
  (noise 'white 1.0)
  '(730 1090))
```

The formants still imprint the vowel identity, even without a periodic source.

---

## 9. A Breathy Vowel

Mix noise with the sawtooth to produce a breathy or intimate vocal quality:

```scheme
;; Breathy \"oo\" — sawtooth + noise through the same formants
(define source
  (list
    (wave 'saw 180 1.0)
    (* 0.3 (noise 'white 1.0))))

(add-formant source '(300 870))
```

The formants at 300 and 870 Hz define \"oo\"; the noise layer adds air.

---

## 10. A Sung Melody on \"Ah\"

Use the vowel as an instrument and sing a melody—four notes, each shaped by the same formants:

```scheme
;; Melody sung on \"ah\": C D E C
(define (sung-note freq dur)
  (add-formant
    (wave 'saw freq dur)
    '(730 1090)))

(list
  (sung-note 262 0.4)  ; C
  (sung-note 294 0.4)  ; D
  (sung-note 330 0.4)  ; E
  (sung-note 262 0.4)) ; C
```

Same formants, melody in the fundamental. This is how synthesizers produce vowel pads.

---

## 11. An Envelope on the Vowel

Apply an ADSR envelope so the vowel swells in and fades out, like a choir sustain:

```scheme
;; \"Ah\" vowel with slow swell
(define vowel-tone
  (add-formant
    (wave 'saw 150 3.0)
    '(730 1090)))

(adsr vowel-tone :a 0.8 :d 0.2 :s 0.7 :r 1.0)
```

*[needs: adsr]*  
<!-- BUILD: adsr verb — apply envelope to audio buffer -->

The attack is 0.8 seconds; the vowel blooms gently.

---

## 12. Two Vowels, One Note

Morph from \"oo\" to \"ah\" by crossfading two vowels over the same sustained pitch:

```scheme
;; Morph from \"oo\" to \"ah\" over two seconds
(define pitch 140)

(list
  (* 1.0 (add-formant (wave 'saw pitch 2.0) '(300 870)))   ; oo, full volume
  (* 0.0 (add-formant (wave 'saw pitch 2.0) '(730 1090)))) ; ah, silent

;; In a real morph, the multipliers would ramp 1→0 and 0→1 over time.
```

*[needs: crossfade or amplitude automation]*  
<!-- BUILD: crossfade verb or per-sample gain envelope -->

The example shows the structure; the engine does not yet automate gain over time. The listener would hear a smooth vowel change as the formants slide.

---

## 13. A Formant Sweep

Sweep F1 from 300 to 730 Hz over one second while F2 stays constant. This morphs \"oo\" → \"ah\":

```scheme
;; Formant sweep: oo → ah (F1 sweeps, F2 fixed)
;; Conceptual — requires time-varying formant or wavetable interpolation
(define base (wave 'saw 140 1.0))

;; Start formants
(add-formant base '(300 870))

;; End formants
(add-formant base '(730 870))
```

*[needs: time-varying formant or parameter automation]*  
<!-- BUILD: formant sweep — interpolate formant center frequencies over duration -->

The snippet shows the endpoints. A real sweep would require per-sample or per-frame formant interpolation.

---

## 14. A Voiced Consonant

The consonant \"v\" is noise filtered through a narrow band around 1400 Hz, mixed with a low-amplitude buzz:

```scheme
;; Voiced \"v\" consonant — noise + buzz through a narrow formant
(define v-sound
  (list
    (* 0.6 (filter 'bandpass (noise 'white 0.2) :cutoff 1400 :q 10))
    (* 0.2 (wave 'saw 120 0.2))))

v-sound
```

*[needs: filter verb with :cutoff and :q]*  
<!-- BUILD: filter verb — bandpass with center frequency and Q -->

The noise dominates; the buzz adds voicing.

---

## 15. An Unvoiced Consonant

The \"s\" consonant is high-frequency noise, no voicing:

```scheme
;; Unvoiced \"s\" consonant
(filter 'highpass (noise 'white 0.15) :cutoff 4000 :q 1)
```

*[needs: filter verb with :cutoff and :q]*  
<!-- BUILD: filter verb — highpass with cutoff -->

The highpass at 4000 Hz isolates the hiss.

---

## 16. A \"Bah\" Syllable

Concatenate a \"b\" burst (brief silence or click) with an \"ah\" vowel:

```scheme
;; \"Bah\" syllable: brief silence (b closure) + ah vowel
(list
  (* 0.0 (wave 'saw 140 0.05))  ; silence (b closure)
  (add-formant (wave 'saw 140 0.4) '(730 1090))) ; ah
```

The first element is silent; the second is the vowel. A real \"b\" would include a burst of noise at release.

---

## 17. A Robotic Voice

Use a triangle wave instead of a sawtooth for a cleaner, more synthetic buzz:

```scheme
;; Robotic \"ee\" — triangle source
(add-formant
  (wave 'triangle 100 1.0)
  '(270 2300))
```

The triangle has fewer harmonics than the sawtooth, so the vowel sounds less human, more mechanical.

---

## 18. A Child's Voice

Raise the fundamental to 280 Hz and use the same formants:

```scheme
;; Child's \"ah\" at 280 Hz
(add-formant
  (wave 'saw 280 0.8)
  '(730 1090))
```

The high pitch and short duration evoke a child's voice.

---

## 19. A Vowel Drone

Sustain a single vowel for eight seconds as a drone or meditation tone:

```scheme
;; Long \"oo\" drone
(add-formant
  (wave 'saw 110 8.0)
  '(300 870))
```

The low pitch and long duration produce a bass vowel pad.

---

## 20. A Formant Chord

Stack three vowels at different pitches and pan them (conceptually) to produce a vowel chord:

```scheme
;; Vowel chord: \"ah\" at three pitches
(define base 110)

(list
  (add-formant (wave 'saw (* base 1.0) 2.0) '(730 1090))   ; root
  (add-formant (wave 'saw (* base 1.2) 2.0) '(730 1090))   ; minor third
  (add-formant (wave 'saw (* base 1.5) 2.0) '(730 1090)))  ; fifth
```

Same vowel, minor triad. The formants stay constant; the harmony is in the fundamentals.

---

## 21. A Vowel Arpeggio

Arpeggiate a triad on the vowel \"ee,\" one note per beat:

```scheme
;; \"ee\" arpeggio: C E G C
(define (ee-note freq)
  (add-formant (wave 'saw freq 0.5) '(270 2300)))

(list
  (ee-note 262)  ; C
  (ee-note 330)  ; E
  (ee-note 392)  ; G
  (ee-note 524)) ; C
```

The bright F2 at 2300 Hz gives each note the \"ee\" character.

---

## 22. A \"Hello\" Approximation

Concatenate vowels and consonants to approximate \"hello\":

```scheme
;; Rough \"hello\": h + eh + l + oo
(list
  (filter 'highpass (noise 'white 0.1) :cutoff 3000 :q 1)  ; h
  (add-formant (wave 'saw 140 0.2) '(530 1840))            ; eh
  (add-formant (wave 'saw 140 0.15) '(400 1200))           ; l (approximation)
  (add-formant (wave 'saw 140 0.3) '(300 870)))            ; oo
```

*[needs: filter verb]*  
<!-- BUILD: filter verb with highpass -->

This is a sketch—real speech requires more precise timing and formant transitions.

---

## 23. A Formant Table as Data

Define a lookup table mapping vowel names to formant pairs:

```scheme
;; Vowel formant table
(define vowel-formants
  '((ah 730 1090)
    (eh 530 1840)
    (ee 270 2300)
    (oo 300 870)
    (aw 570 840)))

(define (sing-vowel name pitch dur)
  (let ((entry (assoc name vowel-formants)))
    (add-formant
      (wave 'saw pitch dur)
      (cdr entry))))

;; Sing \"ah\" at 150 Hz for 1 second
(sing-vowel 'ah 150 1.0)
```

The table makes it easy to sing any vowel by name.

---

## 24. A Vowel Sequence from a List

Map over a list of vowel names to produce a phrase:

```scheme
;; Sing a sequence: ah-ee-oo
(define vowel-formants
  '((ah 730 1090)
    (eh 530 1840)
    (ee 270 2300)
    (oo 300 870)))

(define (sing-vowel name pitch dur)
  (let ((entry (assoc name vowel-formants)))
    (add-formant
      (wave 'saw pitch dur)
      (cdr entry))))

(map (lambda (v) (sing-vowel v 150 0.4))
     '(ah ee oo))
```

The output is a list of three vowel sounds.

---

## 25. A Vowel Melody

Map over a list of pitch/vowel pairs:

```scheme
;; Melody with vowels: C-ah, E-ee, G-oo, C-ah
(define vowel-formants
  '((ah 730 1090)
    (ee 270 2300)
    (oo 300 870)))

(define (sing-vowel name pitch dur)
  (let ((entry (assoc name vowel-formants)))
    (add-formant
      (wave 'saw pitch dur)
      (cdr entry))))

(map (lambda (pair)
       (sing-vowel (car pair) (cadr pair) 0.4))
     '((ah 262)
       (ee 330)
       (oo 392)
       (ah 262)))
```

Each note has its own vowel and pitch.

---

## 26. A Formant Cloud

Randomize the formant frequencies slightly to produce a chorus of voices, each with a subtly different vowel color:

```scheme
;; Vowel cloud: five \"ah\" voices with randomized formants
(define (random-offset base range)
  (+ base (- (random range) (/ range 2))))

(map (lambda (i)
       (add-formant
         (wave 'saw 150 2.0)
         (list (random-offset 730 50)
               (random-offset 1090 100))))
     '(1 2 3 4 5))
```

*[needs: random verb]*  
<!-- BUILD: random verb — (random n) returns float 0..n -->

Each voice has formants near 730 and 1090 Hz, but not exactly—like a choir where each singer's vocal tract is slightly different.

---

## 27. A Vowel Pad Instrument

Define a vowel-pad instrument that plays a sustained vowel at any pitch:

```scheme
;; Vowel pad instrument — plays \"ah\" at the given pitch
(define (vowel-pad pitch dur)
  (add-formant
    (wave 'saw pitch dur)
    '(730 1090)))

;; Play a chord
(list
  (vowel-pad 130 3.0)   ; root
  (vowel-pad 165 3.0)   ; major third
  (vowel-pad 196 3.0))  ; fifth
```

This is the basis for synthesizer \"choir\" presets.

---

## 28. Text to Speech (TTS) — The Concept

Text-to-speech converts a string of written words into audio. The engine must:

1. Parse the text into phonemes (the smallest units of sound).
2. Map each phoneme to a synthesis recipe (formants, noise, duration).
3. Concatenate the phonemes with appropriate transitions and prosody (pitch, rhythm, stress).

Modern TTS engines use deep learning and large corpora, but the Scheme interface is simple:

```scheme
;; Text-to-speech: convert a string to audio
(speech/say \"Hello, Motoi.\")
```

*[needs: speech/say verb — TTS engine or cloud integration]*  
<!-- BUILD: speech/say — integrate TTS model or API; return audio buffer -->

The verb accepts a string and returns an audio buffer. The implementation is flagged as an engine gap—teach the concept, show the Scheme, mark the seam.

